        <h3 class="article__heading">01. Challenge</h3>

        <p>Groups Recover Together is a healthcare organization that provides medication-assisted treatment for its 6,000+ members who are struggling with opioid addiction. Their comprehensive approach to addiction treatment combines medication, group counseling, and peer support to help members on their journey to recovery. They have 80+ treatment centers across the United States, as well as a telehealth offering that I designed <a class="anchor-body" href="/case-studies/groups" target="_blank">back in 2020</a> as a Product Design contractor at thoughtbot. I joined Groups' Product Team in April 2022 as a full-time Senior Product Designer.</p>

        <p>Goal setting is the hallmark of the Groups experience, and is what sets them apart from their competitors. Not only are members attending weekly group therapy sessions, they are also setting and achieving long- and short-term goals, with the help of their counselors. This set of goals is called a Care Plan, and members create one when they join Groups, and update it every ten weeks.</p>

        <p>While the idea is solid, the execution has been not so great over the years. Before Groups introduced their <a class="anchor-body" href="/case-studies/groups" target="_blank">telehealth experience</a> in 2020, Care Plans were paper-based. Counselors would print them, sit with members in-person, fill them out, and scan them back into the EHR. The process was inefficient and was near impossible to track and find trends.</p>

        <p>When I joined Groups in 2020 as a thoughtbot contractor, I designed their first <a class="anchor-body" href="/case-studies/groups#treatmentplan" target="_blank">digital Care Plan</a> (formally Treatment Plan) as part of their brand new member app. In this app, members could join their group sessions virtually, as well as submit drug screenings and update their Care Plans. It was an incredible leap forward, and gave members the tools they needed to stay engaged and in care.</p>

        <p>Fast forward three years later to now. We have since learned a lot about Care Planning, and the member experience has gone through a few iterations to accommodate updates to the program. While we've changed the Care Plans to fit our program needs, our next iteration involves changing it to meet member and staff needs.</p>


        <h3 class="article__heading">02. Design</h3>

        <p>This was a particularly meaty project, because it involved rethinking how we approach goal setting at Groups ‚Äì  for both the members and the staff. The major piece of feedback we've heard from members is that they want to be able to write goals in their own words. Care Plans have always featured canned goals that members can choose from. Therefore, members bend their goals to fit into our choices, but they always fall short. On the staff side, we've repeatably heard the desire for more visibility and accountability around goal setting. Counselors want an easy way to see their members' current and past goals, as well as a history of all actions taken by themselves, members, and other staff members.</p>


